properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An extended period of very warm to hot weather is expected. Time span: continuing into Friday and possibly Saturday. Maximum daytime temperatures: 30 to 35 degrees Celsius (Humidex 36 to 39) on Thursday and Friday. Cooler conditions are expected along parts of the coast. Minimum overnight temperatures: 18 to 21 degrees Celsius. Locations: New Brunswick. Remarks: Very high temperatures will dominate over New Brunswick for the next several days. The warmest conditions are expected to occur over most areas on Thursday and Friday with cooler temperatures over northeastern parts of the province on Saturday. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. Heat warnings are issued when very high temperature or humidity conditions are expected to pose an elevated risk of heat illnesses, such as heat stroke or heat exhaustion. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of squalls with wind gusts up to 50 knots, frequent lightning, hail and poor to very poor visibility in thunderstorms heavy at times. A north to south line of thunderstorms near the Red River Valley of Manitoba and North Dakota is moving east and may reach Lake of the Woods around 10.00 PM CDT. Some of these storms have the potential to become severe. The main threats are wind and hail. There is also a chance of risk of an isolated tornado. Sudden near zero visibility in torrential downpours is also possible. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. For more information monitor Canadian Coast Guard radio or Weatheradio stations.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of dangerous thunderstorms that may be capable of producing damaging wind gusts, damaging hail and torrential rain. A cold front tracking eastwards across southern Manitoba is triggering thunderstorms this evening. These thunderstorms will rapidly become severe. This severe thunderstorm watch may be upgraded to a tornado watch as conditions continue to evolve and are closely monitored. The threat for severe thunderstorms will diminish late this evening as the cold front exits the province. ### Remember, severe thunderstorms can produce tornadoes. Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
